    {
        "content": "<p>I think the answer will vary greatly depending on what exactly you want to do. The meaning and rigor of the usage of \"differential forms\" by a physicist is significantly different from that of a mathematician, and you have to be quite precise about what you actually want to prove.</p>\n<p>If you just want to show that <code>PV=nRT</code> implies  <code>PV^Î³ = const</code> given some assumptions, it's probably not very difficult and may not require differential forms (in the mathematical sense) at all, instead it's just manipulating derivatives etc. </p>\n<p>doing thermodynamics \"properly\" is an entirely different beast and my limited knowledge is that there are some very advanced manifold theory involved. Even setting this up would probably be a huge effort.</p>\n<p>If you're just getting into this and not really sure yet, I'd also recommend checking out <a class=\"stream\" data-stream-id=\"479953\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/479953-PhysLean\">#PhysLean</a> or <a class=\"stream\" data-stream-id=\"395462\" href=\"/#narrow/channel/395462-Natural-sciences\">#Natural sciences</a>, where you may get more specific advice.</p>",
        "id": 554743980,
        "sender_full_name": "ZhiKai Pong",
        "timestamp": 1762792437
    },
